        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated by CD’s reference to working on the proofs of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2469A.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Lyell to T. H. Huxley, 17 June 1859</ref>. CD had read <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3300.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Haldeman 1843–4</ref> in May 1845 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 4, Appendix IV, 119: 16a). <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2056.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Samuel Steman Haldeman’s</ref> paper discussed the geographical distribution of species. CD’s abstract of this paper is in DAR 74: 163–4. He cited it in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5799.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Natural selection</hi></ref>, p. 116, in his chapter on variation under nature. Lyell recorded the work in his species journal after a long entry, made on or about 17 June 1859, considering the progression of fossil forms (Wilson ed. 1970, p. 262).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3300.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Haldeman 1843–4</ref>, pp. 475–6.</note>
